WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
But first thing now, can you just tell us your name and where you were born, both in English and also in Urdu?

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Urdu is not my language.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
What is your language?

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
My language is Gujarati, but there's not many Gujaratis in Nepal.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:20.000
Are you okay to say it in English and Gujarati?

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:22.000
You have to have the two languages.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:25.000
It would be great. I would like to hear. I don't even know what it sounds like actually.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Can you speak Urdu?

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I can't speak Urdu. It's okay.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.000
Okay?

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:31.000
Yeah.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Okay. My name is Yasmin Jetwa. I was born in Africa, in East Africa, in Uganda.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
And my birthplace was Kampala.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And in 1971, when EDM had overthrown the country, we were overthrown to different countries.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:00.000
But because my mum had a British passport, we ended up in Britain as refugees.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:06.000
But loads and loads of us came. So they were all scattered to Canada and India and Rome.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.000
My dad went to Rome because he had a citizenship for that country. He couldn't join us.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:19.000
And my uncle. And so when we come to Britain, it was October 1971, I think.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
And it was snowing that time.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:32.000
So the charity, there's charity, they're very popular.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Red Cross came to receive us on the bottom of the plain.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Took us to the camps. And the camp was in North Wales.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And it was a RAF camp. There was a big camp, but they were not occupied by them.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
It was empty. So they replaced all the refugees in there.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Since two different places, but we ended up there anyway.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
We were well looked after. They took lovely care of us.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Given us each and everything. Because when we came, we did an Avna thing.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:05.000
On your suitcase?

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
And we were only, I was only young then. I think I was about 14.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And we stayed there. After a couple of months, they moved us to Leamington Spa in Warwickshire.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:23.000
And then from there we stayed a couple of months, still refugees.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
Then we went to Kensington in London.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:29.000
In a big posh building they put us all in there.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.000
And then from there I think we had to decide where we would like to go.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And to settle down. So they gave us a couple of choices.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
But we couldn't decide because my dad and my uncle was not still here.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:49.000
They were in Rome. So we had to wait for them to come over to join us.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:54.000
So our family, my uncle, auntie's family, we were together with the children.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:00.000
So when they came, then they sent them to Pontypryd and other different places.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.000
They gave you a couple of choices. So when they, both uncle and my dad went to Pontypryd.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
When they seen the sceneries, they were so beautiful and greenery.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And they thought, oh wow, they were somewhere in Kashmir.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:17.000
So we had three houses between two families.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.000
And from A to Z they provided us in the house. Everything brand new.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:28.000
We were six siblings, my mom and dad.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
So there was eight of us. They gave us one one of each of one one thing.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
But they done it all nice for us, looked after us.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.000
So we started going to school. But I was never ever interested in school.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
In Uganda the English was compulsory. That was your language.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Their language, native, that was the next language, but very important language.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
So I knew how to speak English anyway.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
So I went to the school over there in Pontypryd for a couple of months.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Till I think I come to sixteen. Then I had a Saturday job.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
And then from that onwards I just worked, worked.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:17.000
And after in 1976 I married and moved to Newport.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.000
And ever since I live in Newport.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:29.000
I was still working till 1990. In between I had my children.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
So I stopped in 1990. Then I became a housewife.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:38.000
I'm from housewife. I found out slowly slowly there's some groups around.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.000
I went to computer classes and some sewing classes.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
And we met some of the friends which we are here. We met through the some.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
From that I started going more and more and more out.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Different groups. See any people. I talk to them and find out is there anything happening.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And since that time I just kept occupied of myself and got involved with so many groups.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:10.000
But my age alive group was first. Which I got committed to it.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
So I think it started in 2008. Is that right?

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Because I'm terrible with the dates you know.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Very first when Leon Taylor started the group.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Can you remember when you were about like 9 years old or 8 years old.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
And what that was like growing up in Uganda.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
My memory is not too good but I can just think of some things.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
It was very hardship growing up.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
Because we were not high class. We were not well off. We were just in between.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:48.000
My dad was just working and over there women stayed home. My mum stayed home.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And the kids were only small then you know.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And me and my sister was brought up at my grandmother's house.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
While she was 10 and I was 12.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
Because we had to look after her.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Because she had a stroke and all that.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And the rest of the family started moving out to other different countries.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.000
So our childhood was a bit of a sad.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:16.000
Because we couldn't go to school anything. Because we were busy looking after granny.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:21.000
But in between my auntie did try to put us in school to go and study you know.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
So we had a bit of education from there not too much.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
The childhood was ok but hard time.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
We seen the poverty and we seen the hard times.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And when the curfews and things were happening before we were thrown out.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:42.000
You know we were looking after my grandmother and my sister.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
It was very scary.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
My auntie was living next door but they were not much involved.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
So me and my sister we seen a hardship since childhood.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:58.000
What would you say that taught you? Is there anything that taught you?

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
That was teaching you around that time?

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
It taught us to see how people are to you.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And if you are not well off person or something.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
You don't count it like you know.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
When you are a basic person you don't count in that society.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And even your relatives put you down.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.000
Because we didn't have a house or anything. We just had a rented property.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
But the rest of the families were well off.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
We were the low ones.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:32.000
But we survived and from that it teaches you about poverty and all that.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Because we had gone through that. We got that feeling.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:40.000
And when we see these Simon Seeker coming or they have got nothing you feel for them.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
You can relate can't you?

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
That related is that.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
Because I say to my sister sometimes she wears things.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
I say don't forget your past.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
You were brought up in a very simple way.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.000
So you know don't forget your past.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
Keep your past on.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
So then you are what?

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
You said twelve you came over here.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
Twelve to fourteen.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Fourteen.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
You were coming over here.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
What was that adjustment period?

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
The changing over.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
What was that like for you?

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
Having to start.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
Being settled in a new life and things like that.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
It was very very different from there.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
Totally different.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
First the snow was snowing.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
So it was so cold we never seen snow.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.000
But going through that we went to the camp.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
All the people who were there never bought.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
We became like families.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
But they had school in the camp as well.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
Everything was provided in the doctor.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
Everything.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
It was just like a little shopping.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
You know like your own camp with everything.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
Facilities in there.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
We had entertainments.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
They used to take us out on the day trips.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
They gave us a lot and they did a lot for us.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So going through that it was giving us a happy moment.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
Because we had never seen that over there.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Especially our family you know.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And though my dad was not there so we were happy.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
And we were happy.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
And we were happy.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And though my dad was not there so these people were looking after us as well.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So the experience was coming good.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
But after settling in Pontypridd it was hard.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Because we were in a community where there was no Asians or anybody.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
In a Welsh community.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:26.000
And in the beginning we had a hard time.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.000
But after I started working they all became my friends.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:34.000
And everybody knew you because it was a small village there.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.000
So that was keeping us happy then.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.000
And what would you say was your favourite memory from that time?

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
My favourite memory?

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Because you were not married and you were just free.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
And you had friends.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
You did so many things together.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
Committed to anything.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
And that was happy moments isn't it?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
You were free then isn't it?

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Yes.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:10.000
What would you say was the most important thing that you had to leave behind?

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
In Africa?

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
Yeah.

